<h2 id="integration-ecosystem">🔌 Integration Ecosystem</h2>

Rezdy's open API philosophy means better integration with your existing tools. Direct connections exist for:
<ul>
<li>Accounting: QuickBooks, Xero, MYOB</li>
<li>Marketing: Mailchimp, Klaviyo, HubSpot</li>
<li>CRM: Salesforce, Zoho, custom solutions</li>
<li>Analytics: Google Analytics 4, custom dashboards</li>
<li>Operations: Zapier for everything else</li>
</ul>

FareHarbor's integration list is shorter but covers essentials. Their Zapier connection handles most use cases, though with less depth than direct API access.

<div class="callout-blue">
<strong>Pro Tip:</strong> Before committing to either platform, document every tool in your current tech stack. Test critical integrations during trial periods. We've seen operators discover post-migration that their waiver system or CRM doesn't play nicely with the new platform.
</div>

<h2 id="support-reliability">🛟 Support and Reliability</h2>

FareHarbor's support is genuinely exceptional. Phone support with knowledgeable humans, fast response times, and proactive account management for larger operators. This matters when you have 200 customers waiting for a kayak tour and your booking system glitches.

Rezdy support is competent but slower. Email-first approach with phone support reserved for higher tiers. The Australian headquarters means timezone challenges for American operators — submitting a ticket at 2pm Pacific means waiting until the next morning for response.

Uptime has been comparable across both platforms in our experience — both above 99.9% in 2025-2026. FareHarbor had a notable 4-hour outage in March 2026 affecting payment processing; Rezdy had brief API issues in January affecting channel sync.

<h2 id="final-verdict">🏆 Final Verdict: Rezdy vs FareHarbor 2026</h2>

For operators serious about building scalable tour and activity businesses in 2026, Rezdy delivers better economics and more sophisticated tools. The higher learning curve pays dividends through lower costs, superior distribution management, and genuine platform ownership.

FareHarbor remains the right choice for new operators, small teams without technical resources, and businesses prioritizing simplicity over optimization. Their website services and support quality genuinely reduce barriers to entry.

Our specific recommendations:

<strong>Under $20,000 monthly bookings:</strong> FareHarbor's free entry point and included services outweigh commission costs. Focus on growing the business rather than platform optimization.

<strong>$20,000-$50,000 monthly bookings:</strong> Evaluate carefully. If you have technical capacity, Rezdy likely saves money. If you're owner-operated and time-constrained, FareHarbor's simplicity may be worth the premium.

